    NZ Reserve Bank expected to hike cash rate to two per cent
    New Zealand's Reserve Bank is holding its May cash rate decision today and it's expected to sharply increase interest rates. Sky News Australia discussed the issue with Sky News Business reporter Edward Boyd. "Reserve Bank in New Zealand has been lifting the cash rate sharply, it's at one and a half per cent right now, it's going to get up to two per cent probably by the end of today. "We haven't actually seen inflation start to come down in New Zealand and that's a pretty good indicator for Australia as well. "Our Reserve Bank's lifting the cash rate and so far it hasn't really had any impact on inflation – I think they're going to need to lift it a lot more to start pushing down those inflationary pressures." Mr Boyd said the RBA isn't expecting inflation to start declining until the middle of next year. "It's going to peak at about six per cent headline inflation at the end of this year and slowly start to fall in mid 2023."
    ‘Where in God’s name’: Biden pleas against gun ‘carnage’
    US President Joe Biden has pleaded for the country to act on gun "carnage", saying he was “struck” that mass shootings “rarely happen anywhere else across the world”. Mr Biden said he had been reflecting on his 17-hour flight –returning from the international Quad meeting with Australian and Asian leaders. “What struck me was that this kind of mass shooting rarely happen anywhere else in the world,” he said. “Why are we willing to live with this carnage? Why do we keep letting this happen? Where in God’s name is our backbone … it’s time to act ... we have to do more."

    These Are The Weapons Banned Or Restricted In War

    Updated Russian Crypto Mining Bill Reduces Tax Amnesty for Bitcoin Miners
    In less than a month, the crypto mining bill in the Russian parliament lost several key points, such as the obligation for mining operators to register in a special register and a one-year tax amnesty for all those who registered. According to the reasoning, the previous project would result in federal budget losses. The new draft law “On Mining in the Russian Federation”, dated May 20, appeared in the database of the lower house of the Russian parliament, the State Duma. The document has several significant changes from the previous version, present by the co-sponsors on April 29. While the text remains unchanged in general, the new draft misses the subsection on a register of mining operators, which companies should register in order to continue their work. In the latest version, to start mining, crypto mining companies must register as sole proprietor or self-employed. Companies would follow a standard procedure for company registration. Related: Russia To Include Crypto In Its Tax Code: Here’s What The Rules Could Look Like Another correction swept away the promise of tax amnesty in the first year of registration. The grace period would apply to the clearance of mining equipment, any profits made before the law was passed, and any violations of strict limits on money transfers abroad adopted by the Russian government on March 8. . local media, in its review of the project, the legal department of the State Duma critical registration and tax amnesty initiatives, stating that they could “eventually incur costs on the federal budget”. On April 7, the head of the State Duma’s Financial Markets Committee, Anatoly Aksakov, revealed that changes to the federal tax code regarding crypto should be adopted. by the end of summer parliamentary session.     Tesla's aura fades as its plunging stock highlights the risks it faces
    Chinese consumers “are pissed off, they’re worried about the future,” Dunne said. “It’s a double whammy that Tesla faces in China.” Tesla shares are reacting in part to the same forces rocking stock markets around the world: the war in Ukraine, rising interest rates, the threat of recession, supply chain chaos and soaring coronavirus. ‘inflation. But Tesla shares have fallen far more than other Silicon Valley giants like Apple or Alphabet, the company that owns Google. Tesla accounted for three-quarters of electric cars sold in the United States last year. The company is several years ahead of its competitors in battery and software technology. But two models — the Model 3 sedan and the Model Y sport utility vehicle — accounted for 95% of Tesla’s sales. Its next consumer vehicle, a pickup truck, has been repeatedly delayed and isn’t expected until next year at the earliest. It’s an axiom in the automotive industry that new models drive sales. And competition from Hyundai, Ford and Volkswagen is growing, giving drivers a lot more choice. Jesse Toprak, an auto industry veteran who is a chief analyst at Autonomy, a company that offers electric cars by subscription, said Tesla’s market share will fall below 40% by the end of 2023. , although its sales will continue to grow as the overall market expands. “They’ll have a smaller slice of a bigger pot,” Toprak said. “But their virtual monopoly on U.S. EV sales will slowly diminish.” Tesla already faces stiff competition in Europe, where electric vehicles account for 13% of new car sales. This foreshadows what could happen in the United States, where battery car sales are just starting to take off. Volkswagen, which has invested heavily in electric vehicles, sold 56,000 battery cars in Western Europe in the first three months of the year, second only to Tesla, which sold 58,000, according to figures compiled by Schmidt Automotive Research in Berlin. A bigger puzzle is how the taxidermist and his wife got it. The most likely possibility, according to several experts, is that the variant was circulating more widely in the human population than previously known, and that the couple caught it from another infected person. Another possibility, more speculative, is that they have recovered the variant from another animal species. “Taxisdermists deal with other dead animals,” said Linda Saif, a virologist and immunologist at Ohio State University. But because the cases were detected “weeks to months” after the two fell ill, testing every animal they might have come into contact with “was not feasible or not indicated”, he said. said Lynn Sutfin, Michigan DHHS spokeswoman.
